# Credit Card Benefits Tracker — Cursor Rules
# Stack: Next.js 14 (App Router) · TypeScript · Tailwind CSS · Supabase

## Project overview
A clean, minimal web app where users log in via Google and manually track
which credit card benefits they have used and which are still pending.
Each user has their own dashboard with their own cards and benefit states.

---

## Core rules (always follow these)

- Use TypeScript for every file. Never use plain .js files.
- Use Tailwind CSS for all styling. Never write custom CSS files unless absolutely necessary.
- Use the Next.js App Router (app/ directory). Never use the Pages Router.
- Use functional components with hooks only. Never use class components.
- Keep components small and focused. If a component exceeds ~100 lines, split it.
- Always handle loading states, error states, and empty states in every component.
- Never hardcode data. Always pull from Supabase or pass via props.
- Always use environment variables for keys. Never commit secrets.

---

## Folder structure to follow

app/
  layout.tsx          # Root layout with auth provider
  page.tsx            # Landing / login page
  dashboard/
    page.tsx          # Main user dashboard (list of cards)
  cards/
    [id]/
      page.tsx        # Individual card detail + benefits checklist
components/
  ui/                 # Reusable primitives (Button, Card, Badge, Modal)
  cards/              # Card-specific components (CardTile, BenefitRow, AddCardForm)
  layout/             # Header, Sidebar, PageWrapper
lib/
  supabase/
    client.ts         # Browser-side Supabase client
    server.ts         # Server-side Supabase client (for Server Components)
  types.ts            # All shared TypeScript types and interfaces
  utils.ts            # Helper functions
hooks/
  useCards.ts         # Custom hook for fetching and mutating user's cards
  useBenefits.ts      # Custom hook for benefit state (used/pending)

---

## Supabase rules

- Always use the server-side Supabase client in Server Components and API routes.
- Always use the browser-side Supabase client in Client Components.
- Every database query must filter by the authenticated user's ID (auth.uid()).
  Never return data across users.
- Use Row Level Security (RLS) in Supabase. Assume it is always enabled.
- Use Supabase Auth for Google OAuth. Never build custom auth.

---

## Database schema (reference this when writing queries)

Table: cards
  id          uuid primary key
  user_id     uuid references auth.users
  name        text               -- e.g. "Chase Sapphire Reserve"
  issuer      text               -- e.g. "Chase"
  network     text               -- e.g. "Visa"
  annual_fee  numeric
  created_at  timestamptz

Table: benefits
  id              uuid primary key
  card_id         uuid references cards
  name            text           -- e.g. "$300 Travel Credit"
  description     text
  value           numeric        -- dollar value of the benefit
  period          text           -- "annual" | "monthly" | "quarterly"
  category        text           -- "travel" | "dining" | "entertainment" | "other"
  reset_date      date           -- when the benefit resets

Table: benefit_usage
  id            uuid primary key
  benefit_id    uuid references benefits
  user_id       uuid references auth.users
  used          boolean default false
  used_at       timestamptz
  notes         text

---

## TypeScript types to use

Always import from lib/types.ts. The core types are:

  type Card = {
    id: string
    user_id: string
    name: string
    issuer: string
    network: string
    annual_fee: number
    created_at: string
    benefits?: Benefit[]
  }

  type Benefit = {
    id: string
    card_id: string
    name: string
    description: string
    value: number
    period: 'annual' | 'monthly' | 'quarterly'
    category: 'travel' | 'dining' | 'entertainment' | 'other'
    reset_date: string
    usage?: BenefitUsage
  }

  type BenefitUsage = {
    id: string
    benefit_id: string
    user_id: string
    used: boolean
    used_at: string | null
    notes: string | null
  }

---

## UI & design rules

- Style: clean, minimal, professional. Think Linear or Notion.
- Color palette: white backgrounds, neutral grays, one accent color (use slate + indigo).
- Typography: use the default Next.js/Tailwind font stack (Inter via next/font).
- Spacing: generous padding. Prefer p-6 or p-8 inside cards. Gap of 4-6 between items.
- Cards: use rounded-xl with a subtle border (border border-slate-200) and soft shadow (shadow-sm).
- Buttons: primary = indigo-600 with white text. Secondary = ghost/outline style.
- Badges: used benefits = green (bg-green-100 text-green-700). Pending = amber (bg-amber-100 text-amber-700).
- Never use more than 2 font weights in one view (regular + semibold is enough).
- Always support mobile layout. Use responsive Tailwind classes (sm:, md:, lg:).
- Dark mode is NOT required for v1. Keep it light-only for now.

---

## Component patterns

When building a list of benefits inside a card, use this pattern:
- Each benefit is a row with: checkbox on left, benefit name + description in middle, value badge on right.
- Clicking the checkbox calls a Supabase mutation to toggle benefit_usage.used.
- Optimistically update the UI before the server responds.

When building the card grid on the dashboard:
- Show each card as a tile with: card name, issuer, annual fee, and a mini progress bar
  showing X/Y benefits used.
- Clicking a tile navigates to /cards/[id].

When building forms (add card, add benefit):
- Use controlled inputs with useState.
- Validate before submitting.
- Show a loading spinner on the submit button while the Supabase call is in flight.
- Show a success or error toast after submission.

---

## What NOT to do

- Do not use Redux or any global state library. Supabase + React state is enough.
- Do not use React Query or SWR for v1. Keep data fetching simple.
- Do not use any UI component libraries (MUI, Chakra, shadcn) unless explicitly asked.
  Build components from scratch with Tailwind.
- Do not use the Pages Router or getServerSideProps.
- Do not store sensitive card data (card numbers, CVVs). This app is benefits-only.
- Do not skip loading and error states. Every async operation must have them.
